  "prompt": "Given 9 digits to work with, how many possible combinations of 3 digits are there?",
  "response": "To determine the number of possible combinations of 3 digits chosen from a set of 9 different digits, we can use the formula for combinations. The number of combinations of \\( n \\) items taken \\( r \\) at a time is given by the formula:\n\n\\[\nC(n, r) = \\frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}\n\\]\n\nIn this case, \\( n = 9 \\) and \\( r = 3 \\).\n\nSubstituting these values into the formula, we get:\n\n\\[\nC(9, 3) = \\frac{9!}{3!(9-3)!} = \\frac{9!}{3! \\cdot 6!}\n\\]\n\nNow, let's break this down:\n\n1. Calculate \\( 9! \\) but note that \\( 6! \\) in the denominator will cancel part of it:\n\n\\[\n9! = 9 \\times 8 \\times 7 \\times 6!\n\\]\n\nThis allows us to simplify:\n\n\\[\nC(9, 3) = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7 \\times 6!}{3! \\times 6!}\n\\]\n\nThe \\( 6! \\) cancels out:\n\n\\[\nC(9, 3) = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7}{3!}\n\\]\n\n2. Now calculate \\( 3! \\):\n\n\\[\n3! = 3 \\times 2 \\times 1 = 6\n\\]\n\n3. Substitute this back into the equation:\n\n\\[\nC(9, 3) = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7}{6}\n\\]\n\n4. Calculate \\( 9 \\times 8 \\times 7 \\):\n\n\\[\n9 \\times 8 = 72\n\\]\n\\[\n72 \\times 7 = 504\n\\]\n\n5. Now divide by \\( 6 \\):\n\n\\[\nC(9, 3) = \\frac{504}{6} = 84\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the total number of possible combinations of 3 digits from 9 different digits is \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{84}.\n\\]",
